    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>An <strong>editorial link</strong> is a backlink that another website adds to your content because their editor found it valuable — not because you paid, exchanged, or self-placed it. Google's link-quality guidelines treat editorial links as the strongest signal in the entire link graph, and they typically make up 60-80% of the backlinks on top-ranking pages.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Link type</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Earned · Follow</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content · Off-page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Trust weight</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Highest</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every SEO wants more backlinks. Only editorial links compound safely — the ones you did not chase but earned. This is the link Google was built to reward, and the one AI engines increasingly use to decide who to cite.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is an editorial link?</h2>
        <p>An editorial link is a hyperlink placed on someone else's website by their own editor or writer, pointing to a page on your site, purely because they found it useful for their readers. The defining trait is that <strong>you did not ask, pay, or trade</strong> for it.</p>
        <p>Editorial links usually appear in three formats:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Source citation</strong> — a journalist references your data or study</li>
          <li><strong>Resource mention</strong> — a blogger links to your guide as a "further reading" recommendation</li>
          <li><strong>Contextual link</strong> — a writer links a phrase inside their article body to your explanation of that concept</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance</div>
          <p>Google Search Central defines "editorial links" as the type of backlink they actively want to reward. Their spam guidelines explicitly warn against any scheme that involves <strong>paying, exchanging, or writing content specifically to place a link</strong> — the exact opposite of editorial.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why editorial links matter for SEO</h2>
        <p>Editorial links do three things paid or exchanged links cannot:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>They carry maximum PageRank weight.</strong> Google's link classifier has been public since 2005 — editorial links score highest on the trust axis because they cannot be self-manufactured at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>They are penalty-proof.</strong> Manual actions and algorithmic link penalties (Penguin lineage) target link schemes. Editorial links, by definition, cannot be part of a scheme.</li>
          <li><strong>They compound.</strong> One editorial mention in a high-authority publication attracts more editorial mentions. A single link on Wired or HubSpot often triggers 10-30 secondary citations within 12 months.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How editorial links get earned</h2>
        <p>Editorial links happen when a writer is drafting a piece and needs to cite a source. Their search behaviour is roughly:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Type a query like "email open rate benchmark 2026" into Google</li>
          <li>Click the first two or three results</li>
          <li>Pick the page with the clearest number, freshest date, and most trustworthy author</li>
          <li>Link to it as their source</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Your job is to be that first-two-or-three result — with the number, the date, and the author signal ready.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Editorial link vs other backlink types</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Who placed it</th><th>Cost</th><th>SEO trust</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Editorial link</strong></td>
                <td>Third-party editor</td>
                <td>Free (earned)</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Highest</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Guest-post link</strong></td><td>You (as guest author)</td><td>Time or fee</td><td class="cell-meh">Moderate</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Paid link</strong></td><td>You, via payment</td><td>$$$</td><td class="cell-no">Against Google guidelines</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Directory link</strong></td><td>You (via submission)</td><td>Free or small fee</td><td class="cell-meh">Low</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Reciprocal link</strong></td><td>You + partner site</td><td>Trade a link</td><td class="cell-no">Low / risky</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>PBN link</strong></td><td>You (via owned network)</td><td>Network upkeep</td><td class="cell-no">Against guidelines</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real editorial link examples</h2>
        <p>Three patterns produce most of the editorial links top SEO sites earn.</p>

        <h3>1. Original data study</h3>
        <p>theStacc analysed 12,000 email campaigns to publish "Email open rates by industry — 2026". Within 90 days the page earned 43 editorial citations from HubSpot, Litmus, Mailmodo, and 40 smaller marketing blogs — each writer wanted the specific benchmark number.</p>

        <h3>2. Definitive glossary page</h3>
        <p>A well-structured glossary entry (like this one) becomes the "just link the definition" resource for any writer who needs to reference the term. Rankings + clean formatting = citations.</p>

        <h3>3. First-hand case study</h3>
        <p>An agency publishes "How we recovered a 78% traffic drop after the March 2026 core update" with real screenshots and numbers. Every SEO newsletter for the next quarter cites it because no one else has that story.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Editorial link vs guest post link — which counts more?</h2>
        <p>Both can be follow links on high-authority sites. Google treats them very differently.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Editorial link</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Placed by third-party editor</li>
              <li>You have zero influence over the anchor text</li>
              <li>No content contribution required</li>
              <li>Maximum trust signal</li>
              <li>Cannot be manually penalised</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Guest post link</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Placed by you (as guest author)</li>
              <li>You choose the anchor text</li>
              <li>You wrote the piece around the link</li>
              <li>Moderate trust — often discounted</li>
              <li>At-scale guest posting can trigger penalties</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 ways to earn more editorial links</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Publish original data.</strong> Survey your customers, mine your product, or license a dataset. Anything a writer cannot find elsewhere becomes a citation magnet.</li>
          <li><strong>Update the date, but only when you update the data.</strong> Writers filter for fresh sources. Refresh benchmarks quarterly and republish with the new year in the title.</li>
          <li><strong>Own a specific number.</strong> "Editorial links account for 62% of the backlinks on page-1 SERPs" is the kind of stat writers copy verbatim. Give them one.</li>
          <li><strong>Structure for skimmers.</strong> Tables, bullet lists, and clearly-labelled stats let a hurried journalist grab what they need in 30 seconds and cite you.</li>
          <li><strong>Make the author obvious.</strong> Editorial-trust signals travel with the byline. A named expert with LinkedIn, bio page, and prior citations earns more mentions than an anonymous team byline.</li>
          <li><strong>Promote to reporters, not to SEOs.</strong> Once a study is live, ping journalists who cover your beat with a one-paragraph pitch and the key stat. Never ask for a link — offer the number.</li>
          <li><strong>Turn one asset into three formats.</strong> The same data as a full report, a Twitter thread, and a slide graphic captures citations from writers who prefer different research shortcuts.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — outreach that reads like link-begging</div>
          <p>The moment an email says "would you consider adding a link to our resource," you've stopped earning and started asking. Editors delete those emails. Send the stat, the story, or the visual — and let the link be their idea.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common editorial link mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Chasing DR instead of relevance</strong> — an editorial link from a niche industry blog beats a random mention on a DR90 general-news site.</li>
          <li><strong>Publishing without a claim</strong> — pages that summarise other people's ideas earn few links. Writers cite pages that make an original point.</li>
          <li><strong>Hiding the author</strong> — no byline, no bio, no LinkedIn = fewer citations. Editors want to know who to attribute.</li>
          <li><strong>Mass "resource page" outreach</strong> — modern editors treat this as spam. It converts under 1%.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring unlinked mentions</strong> — brands are often name-dropped without a link. A polite request to hyperlink an existing mention converts far higher than pitching a new link.</li>
        </ul>

